observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed to:

a. Provide budget for technical personnel and competent manpower services to take charge of the operations and enough budget allocation for safeguarding the facility;

c. 	Make representation with EMB Region 6 and Capiz Provincial Government for the continued assistance in the conduct of training and orientation of personnel in charge of the operation and maintenance of the ZWRF;

d. 	Make representation with the Provincial Government to augment the needed funds for the construction of appropriate fencing to safeguard the perimeter;

e. 	Make representation and inform in writing EMB for the immediate replacement of 1 unit of brand-new Biodegradable Waste Shredder which is non-functional/defective upon delivery to serve its purpose efficiently.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Issue an Executive Order formally constituting the Inventory Committee, composed of an adequate number of members, including at least one representative each from the Accounting Unit and the Property Unit, to ensure the proper and timely completion of the physical inventory within a period not exceeding three months, in compliance with Section 5.2 of COA Circular No. 2020-006;
Ensure that future inventory activities are conducted collectively by the Inventory Committee and properly witnessed by the designated COA representative, as required under Sections 5.4 and 5.8 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
Require the Inventory Committee to prepare a detailed Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) and submit the duly approved PIP to the Audit Team at least ten (10) days before the commencement of inventory-taking activities;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to strictly adhere to the documentation requirements by utilizing the standard Inventory Count Form (ICF) daily for each PPE sub-major account group;
Ensure that all PPE items are subjected to physical count, especially those currently missing in the RPCPPE such as land, road networks, flood control systems, buildings, markets, and other structures, to present a complete and reliable report of PPE; and
Direct the GSO-Designate, in coordination with the Accounting Unit, to promptly conduct the reconciliation of their respective property and accounting records based on the completed physical inventory, and ensure its completion within ten (10) days from the submission of the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant, and Equipment (RPCPPE), in accordance with Section 6.3 of COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Direct the Collecting Officers to remit their collections intact daily or at the close of each business day;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to deposit his collections intact daily or not later than the next banking day;
Establish a cut-off date for accepting tax payments at the end of the year to ensure the prompt deposit of collections and to avoid the accumulation of undeposited amounts;
Require all collecting officers to prepare and maintain individual cashbooks to record their daily collections and remittances, and to submit the Monthly Report of Accountability for Accountable Forms (RAAF) using the prescribed format; and
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to monitor the issuance of Accountable Forms and to refrain further issuance of additional Official Receipts to collectors unless remittances of all collections are made and previous accountable forms are clearly accounted in the RAAF.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Relieve the accountable officers who has not been bonded from performing collection functions;
Immediately require all unbonded accountable officers to apply for fidelity bonds in accordance with Treasury Circular No. 02-2019, as a condition for the continued performance of their cash handling functions;
Conduct a thorough review and reassessment of existing fidelity bonds to determine whether current bond coverage is adequate relative to the officers’ cash handling responsibilities, and promptly initiate adjustments where necessary; and
Direct the accountable officers to strictly limit their actual cash accountability to amounts within the coverage of their approved fidelity bond.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Enhance its procurement planning processes to ensure that similar requirements within the same period are identified and consolidated in the Annual Procurement Plan (APP) for the adoption of the appropriate mode of procurement;
Submit the lacking procurement documents, such as the BAC Resolutions recommending the Delegation of Authority and Mode of Procurement, and the proof of PhilGEPS posting, to ensure compliance and completeness of procurement records;
Direct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to strictly adhere to the provisions of the Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184, particularly on the general policy of competitive bidding, and to resort to alternative modes of procurement only when all prescribed conditions are fully met;
Discontinue procurement practices that circumvent the procurement law, including the strict prohibition against splitting of contracts to avoid applicable thresholds and procedures for similar items procured on almost the same period; and
Strengthen internal control mechanisms over procurement activities, with particular emphasis on the role and accountability of the BAC, to uphold the core principles of transparency, equity, efficiency, economy, and reliability in the procurement process.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Require the GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) to ensure that all Programs, Projects, and Activities (PPAs) proposed under the GAD Plan are directly linked to gender issues identified through gender analysis and supported by sex-disaggregated data;
Discontinue the use of GAD budget for social assistance, sports activities, food distribution, and similar programs unless a clear and documented gender issue is being addressed and proper justification is reflected in the GAD plan;
Ensure that all GAD-related disbursements for meals and snacks be supported with complete and appropriate documentation including duly accomplished and labeled attendance sheets with names, dates and signatures, official activity documentation, and photographs showing the actual conduct of the activity rather than just the meals distributed; and
Require the concerned LGU officers to submit key GAD documents to the Audit Team, particularly the GAD Agenda, Harmonized Gender and Development Guidelines (HGDG) tools, and GAD Accomplishment Report.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Strictly enforce compliance with documentation requirements prescribed under Item D of the Manual on Audit for Fuel Consumption of Government Motor Vehicles dated September 1977 particularly the mandatory use and submission of Driver’s Trip Tickets, Requisition and Issue Vouchers (RIVs) or its equivalent, Daily Gas Issue Record, Summary of RIVs, Monthly Report of Official Travels, and Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption;
Require all concerned personnel, particularly those from the General Services Department to ensure that every fuel procurement is properly supported by a duly accomplished and approved RIV and that fuel is issued only upon presentation of a valid Driver’s Trip Ticket;
Institute a proper system of recording and monitoring fuel usage, including the daily encoding of fuel issuance in the Gas Issue Record Book and the preparation of monthly summaries of fuel utilization, to facilitate reconciliation of data and detection of discrepancies;
Ensure that drivers assigned to government vehicles regularly prepare and submit Monthly Reports of Official Travels, clearly stating the trips undertaken, purpose, mileage, and corresponding fuel consumed;
Designate responsible personnel to prepare and consolidate the Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption, which should reflect fuel economy data for each vehicle, and submit the same to the Audit Team for verification purposes; and
Review and improve internal controls over fuel distribution and documentation, and provide necessary training or orientation to accountable officers and personnel involved in fuel requisition, issuance, and monitoring to ensure that they understand and observe the required procedures and documentation standards.

We recommend that Management:
Require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) and the End-User Units to strictly adhere to the procedural guidelines prescribed under Republic Act No. 9184 and the Local Government Units Procurement Manual in the conduct of procurement through competitive bidding;
Enhance internal control mechanisms to ensure that no goods or services are delivered or accepted prior to the issuance and acknowledgment of the Notice to Proceed;
Conduct a review of current procurement practices and address any procedural lapses or weaknesses that may allow early deliveries or unauthorized disbursements.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Require the HRMO to formalize employment arrangements by executing contracts with all Job Order (JO) and Contract of Service workers, clearly defining job descriptions, terms of employment, and compensation, to ensure proper documentation and accountability. Additionally, ensure that such contracts are regularly reviewed and renewed as necessary;
Require the HRMO to develop and implement clear guidelines and standardized policies for the hiring, designation, and management of JO workers, ensuring transparency, efficiency, and compliance with regulations;
Direct the HRMO to conduct a thorough review of each department’s staffing requirements and recommend the hiring of qualified personnel for regular appointments when necessary. This will help regulate the JO employment and ensure that long-term staffing needs are met appropriately; and
Ensure that JO workers are hired strictly based on necessity and urgency by assessing departmental needs and evaluating individual assignments. This will prevent redundancy, duplication of tasks, and inefficiencies in work accomplishments.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Implement a reliable, secure, and centralized timekeeping and attendance recording system such biometric machines or digital bundy clocks to ensure accurate, real-time, and tamper-proof recording of employee attendance. For offices located outside the main municipal hall or in remote areas where the installation of biometric devices may not be feasible, devise an equivalent alternative attendance monitoring system;
Continue using manual logbooks as a secondary measure to confirm attendance and serve as a backup in cases of technical malfunction or system downtime;
Institute and strictly enforce a standardized attendance recording and monitoring policy through the Human Resource Management Office. This includes conduct of regular spot checks and attendance validations; and
Require supporting documents for field assignments and official travel.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Require all concerned officials and employees to strictly comply with the documentary requirements prescribed under COA Circular No. 2012-001, dated June 14, 2012, COA Circular No. 2017-001, dated June 19, 2017, and COA Resolution No. 2021-044, dated December 28, 2021 in processing and liquidating travel expenditures;
Review and validate the contracts of JOs and COS personnel to ensure that only those with valid and subsisting contracts are allowed to travel and incur related expenses charged against government funds;
Issue necessary certifications for JO/COS personnel’s travel claims ensuring that the tasks cannot be performed by regular employees and the travel is necessary to fulfill the obligations of their contracts; and
Disallow any future travel claims that are not supported with complete and valid documentation and return such claims to the concerned offices for completion or correction before processing.

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the cost of completed projects in the books of accounts duly supported with Certificate of Completion, Inspection Reports, and SWA to appropriate PPE accounts upon the date of their completion;



Require the Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate to prepare, maintain and reconcile the Local Road Network Ledger Card and Property Card, respectively; and


Direct the Municipal Accountant to provide proper and complete disclosures in the NTFS.

a.	Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

Stop the practice of outright recognition of expenses, recognize inventory upon receipt of goods, and maintain the necessary perpetual inventory records including the Supplies Ledger Cards for each commodity/stock in accordance with Section114 of the NGAS for LGUs, Volume 1;

Recognize stock issuances only upon the receipt of submitted SSMI with the original copy of the RIS pursuant to Sections 121 of NGAS for LGUs Vol. 1;

b.	Instruct the GSO-Designate to:

1.	Maintain stock cards for supplies to track their receipt and disposal, and reconcile them with the accounting unit’s ledger cards;

2.	Consolidate weekly the Requisition and Issue Slips (RIS) for which supplies and materials were issued using the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) and submit it immediately, along with original copy of the RIS to the Municipal Accountant for the recording of the cost of the supplies and materials issued; and

Conduct a semestral physical count of inventory items by type, prepare the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI), and submit the results to the Auditor concerned not later than July 31 and Jan 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively.

a.	Strictly implement all projects, programs, and activities under the 20% Development Fund;


b.	Include only PPAs that are feasible, and can be completed within the target date of implementation taking into consideration the priorities set by the LGU leadership; and

c.	Closely supervise PPAs implementation and to monitor its execution to immediately address arising problems/issues.

Instruct the General Services Officer-Designate to maintain property cards following the prescribed procedures in property recording and maintain an updated, accurate and complete property records;

Direct the Municipal Accountant and the GSO-Designate to conduct reconciliation of PPE by category and its PPELC and PC records, respectively and prepare adjustment in the books of accounts and the property records, respectively; and

Require the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant to look into and comply with the guidelines and procedures set forth in the COA Circular No. 2020-006 to address issues and concerns on the non-existing and unserviceable assets.

Facilitate the processing of Certificate of Title of the untitled lots in order to establish absolute ownership and protect the legal interest of the LGU thereof pursuant to Section 148 of COA Circular No. 92-386;


Direct the Municipal Assessor to appraise the untitled lots to its current market value and provide the same to the Municipal Accountant for reference in recording in the book of accounts;




Direct the Municipal Treasurer to facilitate and supervise the proper payments of expenses for the land titling and to update and reconcile the inventory of property assets with the updated records of the Municipal Accountant.

7.13	We recommended and the Management agreed to:
a.	Stop charging unnecessary expenses irrelevant to the “Bugas sa Pagbag-o” Program to maximize the use of allocated funds to directly benefit the intended beneficiaries.
b.	Require the Municipal Social Welfare and Development Office (MSWDO) to prepare RIS upon requisition and to submit thereafter, the original copy to the designated GSO to support the SSMI and subsequent recording of expenses;
Instruct the GSO-designate to maintain stock cards for food supplies, consolidate monthly the RIS issued using the SSMI and submit to the Municipal Accountant for recording, and submit the semestral physical count to the Auditor concerned not later than July 31 and Jan. 31 for the first and second semesters, respectively; and
Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to stop the practice of outright recognition of expenses on food supplies, recognize inventory upon receipt of goods, recognize stock issuances only upon the receipt of submitted SSMI with the original copy of the RIS, and maintain the necessary perpetual inventory records including the Supplies Ledger Cards for each commodity/stock in accordance with Sections 114 and 121 of the NGAS for LGUs, Volume 1;

a.	Direct the Municipal Treasurer to prepare/update accordingly the yearly RPTAR of duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year and require the Municipal Accountant to set up an accurate RPT/SET Receivables and recognize Deferred RPT/SET at the beginning of each year;

b.	Direct the Municipal Treasurer to prepare a certified list of real property tax delinquencies of all taxpayers as of December 31, 2022 in order to establish the correct RPT and SET Receivables outstanding balances and submit to the Municipal Accountant to serve as a basis for preparing necessary adjusting entries;

c.	Direct the Municipal Treasurer to intensify tax collection campaign through sending follow-up letters/notices of tax collection to delinquent taxpayers and remind them of their tax obligations.

a.	Expedite the completion of the construction of the MRF and thermal decomposition building which will serve as shelter for the machinery/equipment and ensure that the design is suitable and sufficient to provide protection against corrosion, damage, and exposure to other elements that may affect its operational efficiency;

b.	Provide budget for technical personnel and competent manpower services to take charge of the operations and enough budget allocation for safeguarding the facility;

c.	Make representation with EMB Region 6 and Capiz Provincial Government for the continued assistance in the conduct of training and orientation of personnel in charge of the operation and maintenance of the ZWRF;

d.	Make representation with the Provincial Government to augment the needed funds for the construction of appropriate fencing to safeguard the perimeter;

e.	Make representation and inform in writing EMB for the immediate replacement of 1 unit of brand-new Biodegradable Waste Shredder which is non-functional/defective upon delivery to serve its purpose efficiently, and

f.	Immediately install the solar-powered 4G network camera kit right after the completion of MRF and thermal decomposition building to enable monitoring of the operations of the equipment.

a.	Submit immediately the financial reports and accounts listed in Appendix Y which are already overdue;

b.	Implement adequate measures that will facilitate the timely submission of the financial reports, records of receipts and disbursements, and bank reconciliation statements to facilitate an auditorial review; and

c.	Henceforth, strictly comply with the aforementioned laws, rules, and regulations.

We recommended that:
a)  The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer reconcile the RPT Receivable and SET Receivable recorded in the financial statements against the Certified List of Delinquent Properties and record necessary adjusting entries;
b) The Municipal Accountant reconcile the SET Receivable and Deferred SET and record adjustments for the difference amounting to ₱1,365,338.25 as of December 31, 2019;
c)   The Municipal Accountant ensure that RPT and SET are correctly recorded in accordance with Section 20 and 36, Chapter 3 of the NGAS for LGUs Volume I;

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that Management:
a. Require the MSWDO that during identification of PPA’s for budgeting, propose
only those which are feasible and can be completed within the target date of
implementation, taking into consideration the priorities of the LGU leadership;
b. Strictly implement all LCPC projects, programs and activities in relation to its
Annual Budget;
c. See to it that PPAs being implemented are closely monitored and supervised so
that problems/issues that may arise shall be immediately addressed; and
d. Include the end-result of the activities undertaken in the Accomplishment Report;

Initiate the compilation of information for all items of PPE (current and prior years) at cost or fair value, duly supported with Construction in Progress Ledger Card (CIPLC) through the Offices of LGU’s Engineer and Accountant;
Require the Municipal Accountant to reclassify CIP account to appropriate asset account, as soon as the construction is completed including all expenses during the construction period;
Henceforth, observe accuracy and timely recording and maintenance of CIPLC containing all on-going and uncompleted projects for proper monitoring;
Prepare the specific estimated useful life for each asset based on LGU’s experience on the life of its PPE, copy furnished the Audit Team; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to provide adequate disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements regarding the status of any item in the PPE funded by a loan.

Consider the 20% debt service ceiling and the net available funds prior to loans/borrowings contracting pursuant to DOF LFC No. 1-2012; 
Consider the type/nature and economic or useful life of the properties to be financed and the remaining term of the contracting incumbent official in determining the loan/borrowing terms;
Maintain updated subsidiary ledgers for each loan/borrowings contracted for proper monitoring of the correct balances of the accounts and propriety of expenses charged thereon; and
Consider a competitive rental fees for the Public Market as an additional source of income to cover the annual loan amortization.

Direct the Municipal Assessor to establish proper coordination and linkages with other heads of departments i.e., Treasury and Accounting or with other Local and National Government Agencies i.e., Province, Register of Deeds and DAR among others, to come up with an Assessment Roll (AR) and submit the AR to the Municipal Treasurer for the preparation of RPT Account Register/Taxpayer’s index card; 
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to furnish the Municipal Accountant of a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year; and
Based on the list, direct the Municipal Accountant to draw a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to record the entries debiting RPT/SET Receivables and crediting Deferred RPT Income/Deferred SET Income at the beginning of the year.

Direct the BAC secretariat to furnish the Audit Team with perfected contracts awarded for the period June 2015 to July 2016 as basis of computing the subject honoraria, pursuant to DBM BC 2004-5 and 5A;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that succeeding payment of honoraria are duly supported with complete attachments required for all completed projects or contract; 
Direct the concerned official to submit all completed contracts within the five (5) working days from its execution pursuant to COA Circular 2009-001 dated February 12,2009; and
Require the BAC Secretariat to maintain a log book containing all relevant information on the procurement process up to the award of contract so as to provide bases for granting honorarium and overtime to personnel involve in procurement activities.

Establish GAD agenda or identify priority gender issues using the results of gender analysis and assessment provided by sex-disaggregated data as basis for the formulation of PPAs to be included in the GAD Plan and Budget; 
Identify and include appropriate PPAs that address priority gender issues in the GPB; 
Identify specific gender indicators that would help keep track progress made for purposes of consistency and sustainability of the identified GAD-focused PPAs; 
Determine efficiency and effectiveness of interventions in addressing gender related issues and concerns taking into account the results of PPAs evaluation in terms of benefits to target beneficiaries; and
Review prior year’s audit findings and recommendations viz-a-viz GAD accomplishments to determine the remaining gender issues not addressed in the previous GPB, pursuant to Joint Circular 2012-01 of PCW-NEDA-DBM.

Prioritize the implementation of the identified PPAs based on the LDRRM Plan and monitor PPAs outcomes to ensure that the impact of calamities to peoples’ lives and damage to properties are minimized, if not, totally eliminated; 
Submit justification why the LDRRM focused-PPAs that could best addressed the purposes of Disaster Preparedness and Mitigation to reduce future casualties and property damage are not fully implemented; and
Consider in the planning phase the construction choices of projects funded out of LDRRM fund for long-lasting structures so as to enhance its disaster preparedness and avoid mass casualties and destruction of properties, if possible, establish linkages for other funding opportunities.

Earmark funding support for “Research Study” with the end view of collecting evidence to determine the appropriate PPAs for a more equitable and efficient allocation of SEF budget; 
Direct all concerned DepEd officials, teachers and school heads who are recipient of a financial assistance for travel, various sports and school activities to submit appropriate supporting documents with a view of determining whether the financial assistance was utilized for its intended purpose/s; 
Earmarked bigger budget allocation for the construction/repair of school buildings, classrooms and facilities including furnishing of equipment and furniture for a better learning environment; and
Submit certification from the School Head that the payment of utilities (Water, Electric and Telephone Expenses) were not included in the SIP as approved by the DepEd Superintendent for CY 2016.

On record keeping:
Keep basic record of the operation of SWM System and keep track of the current condition of the dumping site for proper monitoring;
On waste segregation:
Direct the SWM Task Force to strictly enforce solid wastes segregation prior to collection;
On the condition of MRF/dumpsite:
Install MRF using the guidelines and criteria prescribed in RA No. 9003 on sorting, segregation, composting and recycling before final disposal at the sanitary landfill;
On budget constraints:
Establish linkage for possible funding from other sectors of government, non-government organizations and from domestic and foreign sources by way of donations, endowments, grants and contributions to finance the full implementation of SWM Program from collections to proper disposal; and
Encourage private organizations and non-government organizations to join the LGU in its effort of keeping its environment clean, healthy and green.

Direct the Municipal Accountant to revert the unspent balance of appropriations from CY 2014-2015, in accordance with the COA Circular No. 89-302 dated December 29, 1989; 
Direct the concerned officials to implement PPAs identified in the AIP as scheduled/planned pursuant to the DILG-DBM Joint Circular DILG-DBM No. 2011-1 dated April 13, 2011; and
Direct the concerned official to conduct proper monitoring of the fund transferred as well as the provisions of the MOA with the concerned barangays and requires the submission of liquidation reports pursuant to COA Circular No. 94-013.
